:QUOTE
You are not in a darkroom. You are in a changing bag for three minutes. Everything after that is chemistry and timing.

:INFO
What You Actually Need
Developing black and white film requires no darkroom. The only step performed \
in complete darkness is loading the film onto a plastic reel and sealing it \
inside a developing tank. A changing bag replaces the darkroom entirely. Once \
the tank is sealed, every remaining step happens in ordinary room light.

:COUNTER.half
68 Degrees F / 20 Degrees C
Standard developer temperature
|
:COUNTER.half
4 Inversions
Every 30 seconds after the first minute

:PATH
Load the Film in Total Darkness
Practice loading a sacrificial roll in daylight until the motion is automatic. \
The film leader feeds into a slot on the Paterson reel. The reel halves rotate \
back and forth to walk the film inward. Curl the film very slightly as it feeds \
to prevent buckling against the spiral walls. Once fully loaded, drop the reel \
into the tank and press the funnel lid down firmly until it clicks. The changing \
bag can now be opened.

:PATH
Mix and Temper Your Developer
Mix developer to the correct dilution. Standard D-76 is used 1:1 diluted with \
water. Bring the solution to 68°F / 20°C using a water bath — a bowl of warm \
tap water works well. Measure temperature with a thermometer. One degree above \
target accelerates development and raises contrast. One degree below slows it. \
Temperature matters more than any other variable.

:PATH
Develop the Film
Pour developer into the tank quickly and start your timer immediately. For the \
first 30 seconds: constant agitation, steady end-over-end inversions. Then 4 \
inversions every 30 seconds for the remainder of development time. Tap the tank \
firmly on the counter after each agitation burst to dislodge air bubbles on the \
film surface. Development time depends on the film — HP5 Plus at 1:1 D-76 \
takes 11 minutes at 68°F.

:PATH
Stop, Fix, and Wash
At the end of development, pour out the developer and add stop bath for 30 \
seconds with continuous agitation. Stop bath halts development instantly. Pour \
out stop bath and add fixer for 5 to 10 minutes (rapid fixer clears in 2 to 4 \
minutes), agitating the first 30 seconds then 4 inversions every 30 seconds. \
Fixer can be reused until exhausted. Wash for 20 minutes under running water \
or use the Ilford archival wash method.

:COUNTER.half
30 Seconds
Stop bath with constant agitation
|
:COUNTER.half
5 to 10 Minutes
Fixer — agitate first 30 seconds

:PATH
Dry the Film Without Spots
Add 2 drops of Kodak Photo-Flo or a single drop of dish soap to a final rinse \
of distilled water. Swish gently and drain without rinsing again. Open the tank \
and unroll the film carefully. Attach a film clip at each end and hang in a \
dust-free space. A bathroom after a hot shower has ideal humidity to reduce \
static dust attraction. Squeegee very lightly with two wet fingers.

:CHECKLIST
Equipment List
[ ] Paterson Universal Tank (holds 1 or 2 rolls of 35mm)
[ ] Changing bag, double-layered opaque fabric with arm holes
[ ] 35mm canister opener (film picker or bottle opener)
[ ] Thermometer — darkroom type or digital probe
[ ] Timer — phone timer works perfectly
[ ] Graduates: 100ml and 1000ml measuring cylinders
[ ] Film clips or clothespins for hanging negatives to dry

:NOTE
Loading Is the Only Step You Cannot Redo
Scratches running the full length of a roll mean the film dragged on the \
canister lip during extraction. Use a bottle opener to pop the canister top \
completely open before pulling the leader. A dark vertical stripe on one edge \
of every frame means the reel halves were misaligned when threading. Practice \
loading in daylight with a ruined roll until it takes under 90 seconds.

:QUOTE
Development is a conversation between chemistry, time, and temperature. The film remembers everything the camera recorded.

